author: @tronghoang97
text: Interesting facts about Cabbage  1. Ancient roots. Cabbage has been cultivated for longer than almost any other vegetable on record. To be precise, more than 6,000 years! It originated in Shensi Province, China, sometime around 4,000 B.C.  2. Elixir for Baldness. In ancient China (roughly 1000 B.C.) scrolls touted cabbage as a magic cure-all for bald men. It‚Äôs hard to say if there‚Äôs any truth in this claim, but no one can deny cabbage is chock full of nutrients that promote good health.  3. Vitamin C Galore. Cabbage contains a high concentration of Vitamin C. That means it cuts out toxins in your body, preventing skin disease, arthritis, and rheumatism. Go for red cabbage when you have Vitamin C in mind. It contains double the content of regular green cabbage.

author: @sidhantyadav1358
text: I was in the United States up until July 2020, as an international student, and the job market plundered as the cases progressed. For someone like me, fresh out of college, in a different country, and looking for a career in data analytics, everything came crashing down as time progressed. I had no choice but to come back to India and try my hand in the Indian market, which again, has had similar outcomes. I came across your youtube channel and your course recommendations, and I just went ahead and started all over again. It is safe to say that I am making progress, though I haven't landed a job. But the bottom line is that I AM MAKING PROGRESS. And some credit goes to you as well, Sir! Thank you for inspiring me. P.S.: I loved the Barrak Obama on your laptop.

author: @Jsl_516
text: The job market is a steaming pile of cabbage. I‚Äôve got 4 years experience in sports analytics, but I‚Äôve only gotten 9 job interviews in the last 6 months since my lay off. Feels like employer expectations for candidates are sky high because they know they have their pick of the litter. I‚Äôm sick of the gaslighting too. I legitimately didn‚Äôt get one job after 4 rounds of interviews because the manager thought ‚ÄúI have been unemployed for too long already.‚Äù    You were definitely right that most companies are not that open to Remote, and the ones that say they are are still expecting you to relocate. Most of the local companies to me are in hiring freezes. I‚Äôm really not sure what I‚Äôm going to do. I think there was maybe like 5 jobs I could even realistically apply to all of last month. I‚Äôd be shocked if I got a new job before a vaccine was readily available and more companies can start lifting their hiring freezes.

author: @taylorbosier
text: this experience can be summed up as: biggest dumpster fire  normally, wasn't an issue. data jobs were the fastest growing jobs of 2015-2020 until the market took a huge nose dive. now you have people with senior level experience applying to junior level jobs as well as PhDs with who knows what kind of experience. Lots of people are not only graduating and applying to these roles, but a lot of analysts lost their jobs.   So now data jobs are in a huge predicament. If the market doesn't recoil back to equilibrium, companies are going to want even MORE experience than what they already want! I'm seeing 3 years experience needed, and some companies want 5! For entry!   No...I'm not salty about it...
